8. Recommendations
8.1  Raise the self-imposed API limit to 4,500 calls/hr
The single most effective change is to increase API_RATE_LIMIT in the script from 2,000 to 4,500. This is still well within Mist's hard limit of 5,000 calls per hour and retains a 500-call safety buffer. With this change, a full 2,000-site run completes in a single 60-minute window with no pauses — reducing total runtime from 2.2 hours to approximately 20 minutes.
Change this line in the script:
API_RATE_LIMIT = 4500   # was 2000
8.2  Run the script during off-peak hours
Even with a raised limit, scheduling the script to run overnight or during low-traffic periods is good practice. This ensures the API token's call budget is not shared with other tools or dashboards that may be polling the Mist API during business hours.
8.3  Use a dedicated API token for automation
Mist enforces rate limits per API token, not per user. Creating a dedicated SuperUser token exclusively for this script ensures its 5,000-call hourly budget is not consumed by other tools sharing the same token.
8.4  Consider skipping post-change client re-count for large orgs
Post-change verification accounts for 2,020 of the ~4,072 total calls in a full run — nearly half the total. For large organisations where client disruption is unlikely from best-practice WLAN changes (ARP filtering, broadcast filtering, and 802.11r FT changes do not cause client disconnections), this step could be made optional or removed entirely to cut total API usage to approximately 2,050 calls per run.
9. Summary
Metric	Current (2,000/hr limit)	Recommended (4,500/hr limit)
Self-imposed API limit	2,000 calls/hr	4,500 calls/hr
Mist hard limit	5,000 calls/hr	5,000 calls/hr
Safety buffer	50 calls	500 calls
Full-run API calls (2,000 sites)	~4,072	~4,072
Hour windows required	3 windows	1 window
Rate limit pauses	~2 pauses (~100 min total)	None
Estimated total runtime	~2.2 hours	~20 minutes
Max sites — single window	~928 sites	~4,400 sites
Conclusion: The current 2,000-call self-imposed limit is too low for a 2,000-site organisation. Raising it to 4,500 calls/hr eliminates all rate-limit pauses, reduces runtime from 2.2 hours to ~20 minutes, and still keeps the script 500 calls below the Mist platform ceiling.

